<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n28050c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n28" href="#n28050c">N28 (VI.D.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n28all.htm#n28050c"> 50(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> at their perils</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Social Life in Old Dublin]</font> When Parliament was sitting, the Lord Mayor issued a proclamation to this effect: Whereas during the sitting of Parliament the affairs of the publick make it necessary for a great concourse of People to resort to the Parliament House through Dame Street and College Green, and many stoppages and obstructions are occasioned therein by Carts, Carrs, and Drays passing through the same during the said time&dash;For Remedy whereof I do hereby direct all Persons whatsoever (who drive such carriages) not to pass, repass, or go through any part of Dame Street or College Green with their or any of their Carts, Carrs or Drays from the End of Crane Lane to the Parliament House from the hours of Eleven o&apos;clock in the Forenoon to Five o&apos;clock in the Afternoon, and I do hereby require all Persons whatsoever to take Notice thereof <mark>at their Perils</mark>, and the several constables of this city are desired at their Peril to attend from Time to Timne and enforce this Proclamation. <br><font color="green">[Given at the Thorsel Chamber the 12th Oct. 1757. God Save the Queen. THOMAS MEAD.]</font> <small> A. Peter, <a name="APDF1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#APDF1"><cite title="source">Dublin Fragments, social and historic</cite></a> (1925) 22</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
